49:43.000 --> 49:45.000
These are raw materials and components,

49:45.000 --> 49:47.000
unfinished production,

49:47.000 --> 49:49.000
and ready-made production.

49:49.000 --> 49:51.000
In accounting, it is important to talk

49:51.000 --> 49:53.000
about the reserves of raw materials

49:53.000 --> 49:55.000
and components, the input price,

49:55.000 --> 49:57.000
and the price at which it appears in the balance sheet.

49:57.000 --> 49:59.000
This can be the price of acquisition

49:59.000 --> 50:01.000
plus regular logistical costs.

50:01.000 --> 50:03.000
We should not put it into balance

50:03.000 --> 50:05.000
irregular, some extreme events

50:05.000 --> 50:07.000
at the customs, or in the process of transportation

50:07.000 --> 50:09.000
some extreme events occurred.

50:09.000 --> 50:11.000
We should not put it into balance.

50:11.000 --> 50:13.000
We should take this into account

50:13.000 --> 50:15.000
in the period in which

50:15.000 --> 50:17.000
we paid these extreme expenses.

50:17.000 --> 50:19.000
The consumption standards of resources

50:19.000 --> 50:21.000
are an important point

50:21.000 --> 50:23.000
that is important to think about

50:23.000 --> 50:25.000
in accounting.

50:25.000 --> 50:27.000
The order of writing resources

50:27.000 --> 50:29.000
from the production warehouses.

50:29.000 --> 50:31.000
There are several schemes.

50:31.000 --> 50:33.000
There is a so-called FIFO scheme.

50:33.000 --> 50:35.000
It is First In First Out.

50:35.000 --> 50:37.000
The first to be written off

50:37.000 --> 50:39.000
is what came to the warehouse first.

50:39.000 --> 50:41.000
The reverse procedure is called LIFO.

50:41.000 --> 50:43.000
Last In First Out.

50:43.000 --> 50:45.000
The first to be taken from the warehouse

50:45.000 --> 50:47.000
is what came to the warehouse last.

50:47.000 --> 50:49.000
There are two methods

50:49.000 --> 50:51.000
related to the price of acquisition.

50:51.000 --> 50:53.000
They are called HIFO and LOFO.

50:53.000 --> 50:55.000
HIFO is Highest In First Out.

50:55.000 --> 50:57.000
The first to be written off

50:57.000 --> 50:59.000
is what was bought at the most expensive price.

50:59.000 --> 51:01.000
The reverse scheme is LOFO.

51:01.000 --> 51:03.000
Lost In First Out.

51:03.000 --> 51:05.000
The first to be written off

51:05.000 --> 51:07.000
is what was bought at the cheapest price.

51:07.000 --> 51:09.000
There is an option

51:09.000 --> 51:11.000
that the first to be taken from the warehouse

51:11.000 --> 51:13.000
is what came closest

51:13.000 --> 51:15.000
to the expiration of the expiration date.

51:15.000 --> 51:17.000
And as an option,

51:17.000 --> 51:19.000
there is an average scheme.

51:19.000 --> 51:21.000
We consider the average option.

51:21.000 --> 51:23.000
All these options are possible.

51:23.000 --> 51:25.000
It is just important to understand

51:25.000 --> 51:27.000
which of these options

51:27.000 --> 51:29.000
will be acceptable to us.

51:29.000 --> 51:31.000
In international financial reports,

51:31.000 --> 51:33.000
it is recommended to use either FIFO,

51:33.000 --> 51:35.000
that is, the first to come and the first to leave,

51:35.000 --> 51:37.000
or the average option.

51:37.000 --> 51:39.000
Another important point

51:39.000 --> 51:41.000
is the inventory of stocks in the warehouse

51:41.000 --> 51:43.000
and, accordingly, re-evaluation of

51:43.000 --> 51:45.000
problematic positions and non-liquids.

51:45.000 --> 51:47.000
If something is not in the warehouse

51:47.000 --> 51:49.000
or if something in the warehouse

51:49.000 --> 51:51.000
has lost its properties

51:51.000 --> 51:53.000
completely or partially,

51:53.000 --> 51:55.000
or simply went out of fashion,

51:55.000 --> 51:57.000
or was simply bought for the product

51:57.000 --> 51:59.000
that was already removed from production,

51:59.000 --> 52:01.000
it will most likely be evaluated as a non-liquid,

52:01.000 --> 52:03.000
and the price for this non-liquid

52:03.000 --> 52:05.000
may be less than the price

52:05.000 --> 52:07.000
at which it was bought.

52:07.000 --> 52:09.000
Accordingly, the management account

52:09.000 --> 52:11.000
will hang at the price at which we can sell

52:11.000 --> 52:13.000
if it is less than the price

52:13.000 --> 52:15.000
at which it was bought.

52:15.000 --> 52:17.000
Another important point

52:17.000 --> 52:19.000
is the resources in the warehouse,

52:19.000 --> 52:21.000
but there are no necessary papers

52:21.000 --> 52:23.000
that confirm the fact of purchase.

52:23.000 --> 52:25.000
Either there are no stamps,

52:25.000 --> 52:27.000
or there are no signatures.

52:27.000 --> 52:29.000
But in the management account,

52:29.000 --> 52:31.000
we remember that the principle of priority

52:31.000 --> 52:33.000
over the form works.

52:33.000 --> 52:35.000
Accordingly, the paper is not so important,

52:35.000 --> 52:37.000
the fact of having resources in the warehouse

52:37.000 --> 52:39.000
is important.

52:39.000 --> 52:41.000
Further, the stock of unfinished production.

52:41.000 --> 52:43.000
It is very important to think

52:43.000 --> 52:45.000
that the article of costs included

52:45.000 --> 52:47.000
in the base assessment of the stocks

52:47.000 --> 52:49.000
of unfinished production is not included.

52:49.000 --> 52:51.000
If you read the International Financial Report

52:51.000 --> 52:53.000
of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,

52:53.000 --> 52:55.000
it is recommended to assess

52:55.000 --> 52:57.000
the unfinished product lying in the warehouse

52:57.000 --> 52:59.000
according to the production costs,

52:59.000 --> 53:01.000
exclusively according to the production costs.

53:01.000 --> 53:03.000
That is, not a single euro-value,

53:03.000 --> 53:05.000
the costs incurred in the administration

53:05.000 --> 53:07.000
or in the service of marketing and sales

53:07.000 --> 53:09.000
should not participate

53:09.000 --> 53:11.000
in the assessment of the stocks

53:11.000 --> 53:13.000
of unfinished production.

53:13.000 --> 53:15.000
And the finished product, by the way,

53:15.000 --> 53:17.000
which should also be taken into account

53:17.000 --> 53:19.000
according to the production costs.

53:19.000 --> 53:21.000
If everything is fine with it,

53:21.000 --> 53:23.000
if something is wrong with it,

53:23.000 --> 53:25.000
then it is usually recommended

53:25.000 --> 53:27.000
to choose the least of the two,

53:27.000 --> 53:29.000
the production cost or the price

53:29.000 --> 53:31.000
of the possible implementation.

53:31.000 --> 53:33.000
If we can sell the finished product

53:33.000 --> 53:35.000
lying in the warehouse at a price

53:35.000 --> 53:37.000
lower than the production cost,

53:37.000 --> 53:39.000
not to mention the full one,

53:39.000 --> 53:41.000
then we should assess this finished product

53:41.000 --> 53:43.000
according to the price of the implementation.

53:43.000 --> 53:45.000
The least of the two.

53:45.000 --> 53:47.000
The production cost and the price of the implementation.

53:47.000 --> 53:49.000
As for the unfinished production,

53:49.000 --> 53:51.000
imagine that we are talking about windows.

53:51.000 --> 53:53.000
At the entrance we have quite nice boards,

53:53.000 --> 53:55.000
quite nice furniture,

53:55.000 --> 53:57.000
quite nice glass.

53:57.000 --> 53:59.000
At the exit we have a quite nice window.

53:59.000 --> 54:01.000
The unfinished production

54:01.000 --> 54:03.000
is basically wood.

54:03.000 --> 54:05.000
A little stained with paint

54:05.000 --> 54:07.000
pieces of wood,

54:07.000 --> 54:09.000
somehow connected together.

54:09.000 --> 54:11.000
In principle, the buyer

54:11.000 --> 54:13.000
probably cannot find anything

54:13.000 --> 54:15.000
like that.

54:15.000 --> 54:17.000
If we are going to finish this order further,

54:17.000 --> 54:19.000
then we assess it

54:19.000 --> 54:21.000
according to the production cost.

54:21.000 --> 54:23.000
However, if we do not finish the order

54:23.000 --> 54:25.000
for some reason,

54:25.000 --> 54:27.000
we must assess it at the price of firewood.

54:27.000 --> 54:29.000
But as a rule, the unfinished production

54:29.000 --> 54:31.000
is assessed according to the production cost.

54:31.000 --> 54:33.000
As well as the finished product,

54:33.000 --> 54:35.000
if there are no problems with it.

54:35.000 --> 54:37.000
If there are some problems with it,

54:37.000 --> 54:39.000
we suspect that it will not be in demand

54:39.000 --> 54:41.000
on the market,

54:41.000 --> 54:43.000
we must assess it according to the least of the two.

54:43.000 --> 54:45.000
The production cost or the price of the implementation.

54:45.000 --> 54:47.000
Material assets

54:47.000 --> 54:49.000
that consist of equipment,

54:49.000 --> 54:51.000
transport, office equipment, furniture, etc.

54:51.000 --> 54:53.000
What is important here

54:53.000 --> 54:55.000
to think about in accounting policy?

54:55.000 --> 54:57.000
Firstly, it is important to think about

54:57.000 --> 54:59.000
the value-added limit of recognition.

54:59.000 --> 55:01.000
That is, starting from what amount

55:01.000 --> 55:03.000
a certain position of our assets

55:03.000 --> 55:05.000
falls into the list of the main assets.

55:05.000 --> 55:07.000
But it all depends on the company's turnover.

55:07.000 --> 55:09.000
The largest figure that I have seen

55:09.000 --> 55:11.000
in my practice is 20,000 euros.

55:11.000 --> 55:13.000
That is, one large production company

55:13.000 --> 55:15.000
auditors officially allowed

55:15.000 --> 55:17.000
not to include in the list of main assets

55:17.000 --> 55:19.000
objects that cost

55:19.000 --> 55:21.000
less than 20,000 euros.

55:21.000 --> 55:23.000
That is, it all goes into the period

55:23.000 --> 55:25.000
in which it was bought.

55:25.000 --> 55:27.000
According to the MFO.

55:27.000 --> 55:29.000
In the management account,

55:29.000 --> 55:31.000
we ourselves decide

55:31.000 --> 55:33.000
what the value-added limit will be.

55:33.000 --> 55:35.000
I repeat, it all depends on the turnover.

55:35.000 --> 55:37.000
Because in a small hairdresser's

55:37.000 --> 55:39.000
20,000 euros is one thing,

55:39.000 --> 55:41.000
and in a large machine-building holding

55:41.000 --> 55:43.000
20,000 euros is quite different.

55:43.000 --> 55:45.000
So, the auditors may allow

55:45.000 --> 55:47.000
a large machine-building holding

55:47.000 --> 55:49.000
not to include in the list of main assets

55:49.000 --> 55:51.000
positions that cost

55:51.000 --> 55:53.000
less than 20,000 euros,

55:53.000 --> 55:55.000
because for them it is a penny.

55:55.000 --> 55:57.000
And they can relate it to the period.

55:57.000 --> 55:59.000
And in the management account,

55:59.000 --> 56:01.000
even 500 euros is a very large amount.

56:01.000 --> 56:03.000
Therefore, everything above 500 euros

56:03.000 --> 56:05.000
in this small hairdresser's

56:05.000 --> 56:07.000
can be the main asset.

56:07.000 --> 56:09.000
Further, the next point.

56:09.000 --> 56:11.000
When we think about the so-called

56:11.000 --> 56:13.000
amortization, we must understand

56:13.000 --> 56:15.000
what we will amortize.

56:15.000 --> 56:17.000
The cost of purchase,

56:17.000 --> 56:19.000
or the so-called recovery cost.

56:19.000 --> 56:21.000
What is it?

56:21.000 --> 56:23.000
Well, imagine that we are talking

56:23.000 --> 56:25.000
about the release of windows

56:25.000 --> 56:27.000
and when the window is produced,

56:27.000 --> 56:29.000
a calibration-grinding machine

56:29.000 --> 56:31.000
is used,

56:31.000 --> 56:33.000
which was bought for 15,000 euros

56:33.000 --> 56:35.000
and the estimated operating period

56:35.000 --> 56:37.000
is 5 years.

56:37.000 --> 56:39.000
We can amortize 15,000 euros

56:39.000 --> 56:41.000
evenly or not

56:41.000 --> 56:43.000
during this five-year period.

56:43.000 --> 56:45.000
But we ask ourselves,

56:45.000 --> 56:47.000
how much will such a calibration-grinding machine

56:47.000 --> 56:49.000
cost in 5 years,

56:49.000 --> 56:51.000
when we will change this one

56:51.000 --> 56:53.000
to a new version.

56:53.000 --> 56:55.000
We call the company

56:55.000 --> 56:57.000
in which this machine was bought

56:57.000 --> 56:59.000
and ask them,

56:59.000 --> 57:01.000
dear suppliers,

57:01.000 --> 57:03.000
how much will such a machine

57:03.000 --> 57:05.000
cost in 5 years

57:05.000 --> 57:07.000
when we come to you again

57:07.000 --> 57:09.000
and buy a new version.

57:09.000 --> 57:11.000
They will say that about 20,000 euros

57:11.000 --> 57:13.000
will cost a new version,

57:13.000 --> 57:15.000
because the new version of the machine

57:15.000 --> 57:17.000
will consume less electricity,

57:17.000 --> 57:19.000
will be faster to reconfigure

57:19.000 --> 57:21.000
from one product to another,

57:21.000 --> 57:23.000
will have less manual labor,

57:23.000 --> 57:25.000
and will have a new design,

57:25.000 --> 57:27.000
a pretty yellow color,

57:27.000 --> 57:29.000
so the new version will cost

57:29.000 --> 57:31.000
about 20,000 euros.

57:31.000 --> 57:33.000
Accordingly, in the management account

57:33.000 --> 57:35.000
we can amortize 20,000 euros.

57:35.000 --> 57:37.000
The estimated cost,

57:37.000 --> 57:39.000
not the one we paid

57:39.000 --> 57:41.000
for this device

57:41.000 --> 57:43.000
when we bought it.

57:43.000 --> 57:45.000
The alternative option

57:45.000 --> 57:47.000
is to amortize 15,000 euros,

57:47.000 --> 57:49.000
and the remaining 5,000 euros

57:49.000 --> 57:51.000
is accumulated through the reserves,

57:51.000 --> 57:53.000
which we form

57:53.000 --> 57:55.000
to modernize the main park.

57:55.000 --> 57:57.000
The service life, the amortization life.

57:57.000 --> 57:59.000
As a rule, the amortization life

57:59.000 --> 58:01.000
should not be longer than the service life,

58:01.000 --> 58:03.000
than the operating life.

58:03.000 --> 58:05.000
It can be less, but it should not be more.

58:05.000 --> 58:07.000
And we, in fact,

58:07.000 --> 58:09.000
in the accounting policy of the management account,

58:09.000 --> 58:11.000
decide for ourselves

58:11.000 --> 58:13.000
for what period we will amortize

58:13.000 --> 58:15.000
the cost of the main means.

58:15.000 --> 58:17.000
Amortization method.

58:17.000 --> 58:19.000
It can be linear,

58:19.000 --> 58:21.000
when we spread it evenly,

58:21.000 --> 58:23.000
it can be non-linear.

58:23.000 --> 58:25.000
As in the case of a car,

58:25.000 --> 58:27.000
if we assume that the car

58:27.000 --> 58:29.000
loses a lot of cost in the first years of its operation,

58:29.000 --> 58:31.000
and then loses less,

58:31.000 --> 58:33.000
then we can use a non-linear method

58:33.000 --> 58:35.000
for a car or some other similar main means.

58:37.000 --> 58:39.000
As for repairs,

58:39.000 --> 58:41.000
sometimes we have to do repairs

58:41.000 --> 58:43.000
of the main means,

58:43.000 --> 58:45.000
which can be divided into two parts,

58:45.000 --> 58:47.000
cosmetic and cardinal.

58:47.000 --> 58:49.000
The cost of cosmetic repairs

58:49.000 --> 58:51.000
is usually not added to the cost of the main means,

58:51.000 --> 58:53.000
but is related to the period consumption.

58:53.000 --> 58:55.000
The cost of cardinal repairs

58:55.000 --> 58:57.000
is still added to the cost of the main means

58:57.000 --> 58:59.000
in the balance,

58:59.000 --> 59:01.000
because these are quite large sums.

59:01.000 --> 59:03.000
And revaluation of their reserves.

59:03.000 --> 59:05.000
Periodically we should

59:05.000 --> 59:07.000
re-evaluate our main means,

59:07.000 --> 59:09.000
ask ourselves how much we can sell them today,

59:09.000 --> 59:11.000
ask ourselves

59:11.000 --> 59:13.000
how seriously they lost

59:13.000 --> 59:15.000
their properties in the process of operation,

59:15.000 --> 59:17.000
in order to have real figures

59:17.000 --> 59:19.000
in our management balance.

59:19.000 --> 59:21.000
Here is a very useful idea about C-analysis,

59:21.000 --> 59:23.000
because the list of main means

59:23.000 --> 59:25.000
can be very long,

59:25.000 --> 59:27.000
it can be a thick folder.

59:27.000 --> 59:29.000
But according to the Pareto principle,

59:29.000 --> 59:31.000
80% of all this folder

59:31.000 --> 59:33.000
is divided into a 20% list.

59:33.000 --> 59:35.000
80% of the cost of the main means

59:35.000 --> 59:37.000
is 20% of the list.

59:37.000 --> 59:39.000
It is this limited list

59:39.000 --> 59:41.000
that we can re-evaluate for a small amount of money,

59:41.000 --> 59:43.000
and we will hardly re-evaluate the rest of the list,

59:43.000 --> 59:45.000
because it is not worth it.

59:45.000 --> 59:47.000
The biggest problem

59:47.000 --> 59:49.000
in accounting policy

59:49.000 --> 59:51.000
of the management balance

59:51.000 --> 59:53.000
is the evaluation of non-material assets.

59:53.000 --> 59:55.000
The evaluation of non-material assets,

59:55.000 --> 59:57.000
that is, assets that cannot be touched.

59:57.000 --> 59:59.000
What can be attributed to this category?

59:59.000 --> 01:00:01.000
We can attribute all kinds of patents,

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.000
know-how, licenses,

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:05.000
software,

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:07.000
brand,

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:09.000
client base,

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:11.000
management systems

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:13.000
that we have set up in the company,

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:15.000
for example, the quality management system,

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:17.000
the accounting budget management system,

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.000
the CRM system, and so on.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:21.000
All this is very difficult to evaluate in euros,

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:23.000
or in dollars, or in rubles.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.000
But you can try to do it

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:27.000
by applying the so-called cost method.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:29.000
Just add up all the costs

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.000
that we have incurred

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:33.000
to create this non-material asset.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
After that, we will get

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:37.000
the preliminary amount of our balance.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:39.000
Let's look at this scheme.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:41.000
We evaluated our material assets,

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:43.000
our stocks, our main assets,

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:45.000
and so on.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:47.000
We evaluated our financial assets,

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.000
money, debit, financial investments,

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:51.000
and so on.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.000
And now we evaluate our non-material assets

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
using the cost method.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
We evaluate all of them.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:00:59.000
We get the preliminary balance.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:01.000
After that,

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:03.000
we need to read

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:05.000
the literature on the method

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:07.000
of discounted cash flow.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:09.000
This is a method

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:11.000
that can be used

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:13.000
to evaluate the cost of a business.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:15.000
The essence of this method

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:17.000
is that a business costs

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:19.000
as much as it is able to bring

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:21.000
to the buyer in the near future.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:23.000
If a business is able to generate

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:25.000
a lot of money, then it costs a lot.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:27.000
If a business does not bring

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:29.000
a lot of money in the foreseeable future,

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:31.000
then it costs little.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:33.000
Let's say that we predict

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:35.000
that in the next four years

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:37.000
the size of the cash flow

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.000
will be like this.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:41.000
We know that there is a concept

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:43.000
of the cost of money in time,

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:45.000
so we cannot just add

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:47.000
these four quantities.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:49.000
We must first discount them.

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:51.000
The formula is very simple.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:53.000
The future cost,

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:55.000
that is, these columns,

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:57.000
is divided by

01:01:57.000 --> 01:01:59.000
1 plus r

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.000
to the power of n.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:03.000
We get the current cost.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.000
n is the number of periods,

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:07.000
so 1, 2, 3, 4.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:09.000
r is the discount rate.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.000
As a discount rate,

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:13.000
the average costs of capital

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:15.000
are used in this method.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:17.000
How much does the average company

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:19.000
pay for the capital

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:21.000
it uses?

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.000
For the bank, for its own,

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:25.000
for the credit,

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:27.000
it can be calculated.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:29.000
The average costs of capital.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:31.000
We have discounted our columns

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:33.000
and we get the sum

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:35.000
that we compare

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:37.000
with these three blue sections.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:39.000
The sum of material, financial

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:41.000
and non-material assets.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:43.000
The non-material assets,

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:45.000
I emphasize, were evaluated

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:47.000
by the cost method.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:49.000
If we get this amount

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:51.000
using this black method,

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.000
then we must add

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:55.000
the so-called

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:57.000
discount rate.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:59.000
The discount rate

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:01.000
is the so-called

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:03.000
goodwill.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:07.000
This is an English word.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:09.000
Goodwill means

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:11.000
that there is a buyer

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:13.000
who is sane, has a clear memory,

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.000
he is fully informed

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:17.000
about what is happening

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:19.000
in our market,

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.000
and he is willing to pay

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:23.000
this amount for us.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:25.000
In addition to the sum of

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:27.000
material, financial and non-material assets

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:29.000
that are evaluated by the cost method,

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:31.000
if we get this amount

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:33.000
using this black method,

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:37.000
that is,

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:39.000
less than the value

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:41.000
of material, financial and non-material assets

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:43.000
evaluated by the cost method,

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:45.000
we close the balance like this.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:49.000
This means that part of the money

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:51.000
spent on creating non-material assets

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:53.000
has gone to waste.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:55.000
And we close the balance

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:57.000
like this.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:59.000
This means that we overestimated

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:01.000
our non-material assets.

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:03.000
But the common basic principle

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:05.000
that we must always remember

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:07.000
when writing accounting policy

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:09.000
and accounting for applicable assets

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:11.000
is the principle of healthy pessimism

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:13.000
or the principle of observability,

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:15.000
according to which we estimate assets

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:17.000
at a minimum of possible options.

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:19.000
At a minimum.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:21.000
In the case of debts and obligations,

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:23.000
the principle of pessimism

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:25.000
is also observed,

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:27.000
but in this case it means

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:29.000
that we must evaluate our obligations

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.000
and debts to the maximum.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:33.000
In this case, the principle of pessimism

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:35.000
is manifested in this way.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:37.000
In particular, this applies to the assessment

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:39.000
of reserves that we have

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:41.000
in our obligations.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:43.000
In general, there are two types

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:45.000
of reserves in business.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:47.000
There is a reserve, which in English

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:49.000
is called provisions,

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:51.000
and this is, in fact, our obligation to someone.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:53.000
And there are reserves that are

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:55.000
part of our own capital.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:57.000
Here on this slide we see

01:04:57.000 --> 01:04:59.000
the difference between them.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:01.000
Those reserves that we have in our obligations,

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:03.000
in our debts, are called provisions.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:05.000
They can be like this.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:07.000
For example, a company

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:09.000
creates such an interesting

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:11.000
motivation system for staff,

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:13.000
and says, dear employees,

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:15.000
if you work well in our business

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:17.000
for 25 years and after retiring,

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:19.000
we can pay you a pension

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:21.000
together with the state.

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:23.000
You will receive a pension from the state

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:25.000
and from our company.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:27.000
Accordingly, the company

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:29.000
creates reserves for pension payments

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:31.000
to its employees

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:33.000
that they will receive after retiring.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:35.000
The question is,

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:37.000
if an employee retires at 60,

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:39.000
how much more will he last?

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:41.000
If the likelihood of his life

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:43.000
being up to 120 years is high,

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:45.000
then the company must

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:47.000
create a reserve for each employee

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:49.000
for 60 years,

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:51.000
and a monthly salary, and so on.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:53.000
If the likelihood of this is low,

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:55.000
then we create a reserve for less years.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:57.000
But it is better to take it with a margin.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:59.000
The same is true if we create a reserve

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:01.000
for warranty service

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:03.000
of clients

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:05.000
to whom we sold some household equipment.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:07.000
There is a certain likelihood

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:09.000
that all the household equipment

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:11.000
that we sold to clients in May will break down.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:13.000
And we will have to repair everything

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:15.000
for some period of time.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:17.000
But we take a certain period of time

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:19.000
that is quite likely for us.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:21.000
We take the amount of household equipment

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:23.000
that is most likely to break down,

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:25.000
and take this into account

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:27.000
to create a reserve.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.000
Again, a little bit with a margin.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:31.000
We can include such reserves

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:33.000
in our obligations,

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:35.000
treating them as a duty of our company

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:37.000
to our employees or clients.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:39.000
And there are reserves

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:41.000
that are treated as part of our own capital.

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:43.000
For example,

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:45.000
we have a reserve for the modernization

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:47.000
of the main equipment fleet.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:49.000
Remember we said that we have a machine,

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:51.000
and we assume that it will not buy a replacement.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:53.000
Therefore, we amortize the cost of purchase,

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:55.000
but we accumulate some amount

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:57.000
in order to have the opportunity

01:06:57.000 --> 01:06:59.000
to buy a new version

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:01.000
that costs more than the version

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:03.000
that we are already using.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:05.000
Here, in the reserve

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:07.000
on our own capital,

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:09.000
we can include a reserve,

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:11.000
for example, on a dubious

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:13.000
or debitor's debt.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:15.000
The general formula of the balance

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:17.000
in the accounting is very simple.

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:19.000
The capital itself is the assets

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:21.000
estimated at a minimum,

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:23.000
minus the obligations estimated at a maximum.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:25.000
Including the ProVisions reserves

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:27.000
that we create as debts

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:29.000
to our employees, clients, and so on.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:31.000
These are the main rules

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:33.000
of the accounting balance

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:35.000
and accounting policy

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.000
regarding individual assets,

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:39.000
obligations, and our own capital.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:41.000
The second document that is formed

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:43.000
in the accounting policy

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:45.000
is the report on profits and losses,

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.000
where we calculate our income

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.000
and expenses for a certain period.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:51.000
In addition to this,

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:53.000
the accounting policy

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:55.000
also includes a report on the movement

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:57.000
of money funds,

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:59.000
where we collect information

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:01.000
about the income and payments of money.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:03.000
It is important to understand

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:05.000
that we have to have a document

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:07.000
based on the principle of calculations

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:09.000
of income and expenses.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:11.000
In the other hand,

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:13.000
we have a report on the movement

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.000
of money funds,

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:17.000
where we see everything

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:19.000
according to the cash method.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:21.000
Let's look at this slide

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:23.000
to understand the difference.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:25.000
So, there is a period

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:27.000
of January, February, March, April,

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:29.000
May, June.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:31.000
In February,

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:33.000
the company was unloading

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:35.000
its clients

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:37.000
with a certain amount of goods

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:39.000
or services,

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:41.000
and in February,

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:43.000
the revenue is 100,000 UAH.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:45.000
As for the movement of money,

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:47.000
we can see it

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:49.000
in the lower part of the slide.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:51.000
As a prepayment,

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:53.000
the company received

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:55.000
50,000 UAH from its clients in January.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:57.000
In fact,

01:08:57.000 --> 01:08:59.000
the payment of 30,000 UAH in February

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:01.000
is 20,000 UAH as a debit.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:03.000
Accordingly,

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:05.000
100,000 UAH is received in February,

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:07.000
and in January,

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:09.000
February, and March,

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:11.000
50,000 UAH in January,

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:13.000
30,000 UAH in February,

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.000
and 20,000 UAH in March.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:17.000
The same is the case with the payment of expenses.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:19.000
Let's assume that

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:21.000
in April the company took part

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:23.000
in an exhibition.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:25.000
The participation in the exhibition

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
cost the company

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:29.000
a fairly large amount of money,

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:31.000
some 15,000 UAH.

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:33.000
The company paid the money

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:35.000
to the organizer

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:37.000
in April.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.000
The tranche was paid

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:41.000
for 15,000 UAH at the same time.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:43.000
This is evident in the report on the movement of money.

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:45.000
But in the management account,

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:47.000
we prescribe the account

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:49.000
of the so-called expenses of the future periods.

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:51.000
We want some kind of uniformity,

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:53.000
and therefore we spread

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:55.000
this amount for three months.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:57.000
We recognize 5,000 UAH as expenses

01:09:57.000 --> 01:09:59.000
in April, 5,000 UAH as expenses in May,

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
and 5,000 UAH as expenses in June.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:03.000
If we take all this into account in April,

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:05.000
the profit in April

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:07.000
may be very small, or there may be a loss.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:09.000
The profit in May and June may be large.

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:11.000
We want some kind of uniformity,

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:13.000
so we can spread

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:15.000
a fairly large amount of money

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:17.000
spent on the same exhibitions,

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:19.000
for example, on the same advertising,

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:21.000
in the management account

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:23.000
more or less evenly for 3-6 months.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:25.000
Accordingly, in the report on the profits and losses,

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:27.000
in the expenses,

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:29.000
5,000 UAH will be in April,

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:31.000
5,000 UAH in May,

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:33.000
and 5,000 UAH in June.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:35.000
And in the report on the movement of money,

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:37.000
it will be only in one place,

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:39.000
in the place where the tranche was carried out.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:41.000
The money was paid out of the account in April.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:43.000
The expenses in the management account

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:45.000
that are in the report on the profits and losses

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:47.000
are usually divided into four parts.

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:49.000
On the one hand,

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:51.000
the expenses can be divided into constant and variable.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:53.000
This is very useful.

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:55.000
On the other hand,

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:57.000
the expenses can be divided into constant and variable.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:10:59.000
Constant expenses are called

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:01.000
those expenses that do not depend

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:03.000
on the volume of our production.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:05.000
It does not depend on the volume of our production.

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:07.000
If we have a brewery,

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:09.000
we have to pay for the rent,

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:11.000
so to speak,

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:13.000
amortize the capacity,

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:15.000
pay for the work fee of the accounting.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:17.000
It does not depend very much

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:19.000
on how many liters of beer

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:21.000
we were able to brew and sell.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:23.000
These are the so-called constant expenses.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:25.000
What are variable expenses?

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:27.000
These are expenses that depend on

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:29.000
how many liters of beer the brewery

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:31.000
produced and sold in a particular period.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:33.000
Accordingly, if there were many liters of beer,

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:35.000
then the variable expenses are large.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:37.000
If there were few liters produced,

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:39.000
then the variable expenses are smaller.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:41.000
On this graph,

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:43.000
we see that

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:45.000
constant expenses do not depend

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:47.000
on the volume of liters of beer produced.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:49.000
Variable expenses depend.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:51.000
If we sum up the variable expenses,

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.000
we get the total expenses,

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:55.000
which at some point

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:57.000
intersect with the revenue line.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:11:59.000
When they intersect,

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:01.000
we register the so-called

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:03.000
point of non-profitability.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:05.000
At this point,

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:07.000
the company, having produced

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:09.000
a certain number of liters of beer,

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:11.000
has reached zero.

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:13.000
That is, there is no profit yet,

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:15.000
but there are no losses.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:17.000
Starting from this point to the right,

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:19.000
we start making profit.

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:21.000
The more profit to the right, the more profit.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:23.000
It seems to me that many businesses

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:25.000
can benefit from

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:27.000
constant variable expenses.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:29.000
Many businesses can ask themselves

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:31.000
what benefit

01:12:31.000 --> 01:12:33.000
we can get

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:35.000
by transferring expenses

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:37.000
from constant to variable

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:39.000
or vice versa.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:41.000
For example,

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:43.000
if I come to Moscow from time to time

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:45.000
and do not live here permanently,

01:12:45.000 --> 01:12:47.000
it is probably more profitable

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:49.000
to use a hotel.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:51.000
If I do it rarely.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:53.000
If I come to Moscow all the time,

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:55.000
it is more profitable

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:57.000
to rent an apartment.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:12:59.000
I can save money

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
by buying an apartment.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.000
It is also a constant expense.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:05.000
The same is true of a car.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:07.000
If I rarely move from point A to point B,

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:09.000
it is easier for me to call a taxi.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:11.000
These are variable expenses.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:13.000
But if I constantly travel

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:15.000
on a certain route,

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:17.000
it is a constant expense.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:19.000
Not all expenses in business

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:21.000
can be transferred from constant to variable.

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:23.000
But some can be transferred.

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:25.000
It is very useful

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:27.000
to understand the benefits of outsourcing

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:29.000
for your company.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:31.000
The second cut of expenses

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:33.000
is direct and indirect expenses.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:35.000
Direct expenses are those

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:37.000
that can be attributed

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:39.000
to certain types of products.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:41.000
Indirect expenses are expenses

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:43.000
that cannot be attributed.

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:45.000
There are some types of expenses

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:47.000
that can be attributed

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:49.000
to a specific product.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:51.000
They can be considered variable.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:53.000
For example,

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:55.000
if we talk about a brewery,

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:57.000
the water, malt, hops

01:13:57.000 --> 01:13:59.000
are considered direct expenses

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:01.000
when making a certain type of beer.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:03.000
You can clearly determine

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:05.000
the amount of water,

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:07.000
malt, and malt.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:09.000
They can be considered variable

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:11.000
because they depend on liters.

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:13.000
As for constant expenses,

